│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe SLP vectorizer crashes with an assertion        │
│ failure in InstructionsState::getMainOp() while computing costs for a         │
│ TreeEntry. This assertion fires when InstructionsState is invalid (i.e.,      │
│ MainOp or AltOp is null), yet the code attempts to access them. The failure   │
│ occurs during BoUpSLP::getEntryCost when it calls                             │
│ E->getMainOp()/E->getOpcode() for a non-gather entry whose InstructionsState  │
│ wasn't properly initialized.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\n- The pass builds    │
│ multiple vectorization trees. The crash happens when computing costs for a    │
│ 10-lane bundle (the second vectorization attempt), right after calculating    │
│ some entry costs (seen as \"Adding cost ...\" messages), then asserts in      │
│ InstructionsState::getMainOp.\n- The SLP debug trace shows that entries are   │
│ being formed for icmp eq chains, and/or groups that include shl/zext/select   │
│ chains. There is also a message \"Reshuffling scalars not yet supported for   │
│ nodes with padding\", indicating involvement of ReorderIndices/padding logic  │
│ for non-power-of-two VF (here 10).\n- The crash stack shows it is inside      │
│ getEntryCost() after retrieving the opcode/main op from the TreeEntry via     │
│ E->getMainOp()/getOpcode(). This requires a valid InstructionsState inside    │
│ TreeEntry; otherwise, the assert triggers.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\n-      │
│ TreeEntry stores its instruction identity via InstructionsState S. For        │
│ non-gather entries (TreeEntry::Vectorize/Strided/Scatter), S must be valid    │
│ because getEntryCost() unconditionally accesses S.getMainOp()/getOpcode().\n- │
│ TreeEntry creation is performed by BoUpSLP::newTreeEntry. When ReorderIndices │
│ is empty, S is directly taken from the caller: `if (S)                        │
│ Last->setOperations(S);` Otherwise, if ReorderIndices is non-empty, it        │
│ recomputes S: `InstructionsState S = getSameOpcode(Last->Scalars, *TLI); if   │
│ (S) Last->setOperations(S);`. In both branches, if S is invalid, the code     │
│ currently leaves Last->State as set earlier (Vectorize if Bundle is provided) │
│ while not calling setOperations(). This creates a non-gather entry with       │
│ invalid InstructionsState.\n- Later, getEntryCost() assumes a non-gather      │
│ entry has a valid InstructionsState and thus calls                            │
│ E->getMainOp()/getOpcode(), causing the assertion.\n- This situation can be   │
│ triggered for non-power-of-two vector factors or mixed scalars/poison/consts  │
│ when reordering is requested; getSameOpcode may legitimately return invalid   │
│ (e.g., if less than half are instructions). The current code fails to         │
│ downgrade such an entry to a gather.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\nWe should  │
│ ensure that after TreeEntry is constructed, if InstructionsState S is         │
│ invalid, we switch the entry to a gather (NeedToGather) to prevent later code │
│ from accessing S. This must be done in both code paths (with and without      │
│ ReorderIndices):\n\n- Edit 1 (lines ~3651-3656): In the branch where          │
│ ReorderIndices is empty, add an `else` that sets `Last->State =               │
│ TreeEntry::NeedToGather;` when `S` is invalid.\n\n- Edit 2 (lines             │
│ ~3663-3668): In the branch where ReorderIndices is non-empty and              │
│ `getSameOpcode(Last->Scalars, *TLI)` returns invalid, add an `else` setting   │
│ `Last->State = TreeEntry::NeedToGather;`.\n\nWith this change, the subsequent │
│ logic that updates scheduler bundles and asserts about bundles only runs for  │
│ non-gather entries (`if (!Last->isGather())`). Gather entries will follow the │
│ else branch that builds the MustGather map and avoid accessing S in cost      │
│ computation (getEntryCost has an early return for gathers).\n\nPatch          │
│ outline:\n- File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp\n-          │
│ Function: BoUpSLP::newTreeEntry(ArrayRef<Value *> VL, TreeEntry::EntryState   │
│ EntryState, ...)\n- After the existing `if (S) Last->setOperations(S);` in    │
│ both ReorderIndices branches, add an `else` that sets `Last->State =          │
│ TreeEntry::NeedToGather;`.\n\nConcretely:\n\nAt around line 3651:\n  if       │
│ (ReorderIndices.empty()) {\n    Last->Scalars.assign(VL.begin(), VL.end());\n │
│ if (S)\n      Last->setOperations(S);\n    else\n      Last->State =          │
│ TreeEntry::NeedToGather;\n  } else {\n    // ...\n\nAt around line            │
│ 3663-3668:\n    InstructionsState S = getSameOpcode(Last->Scalars, *TLI);\n   │
│ if (S)\n      Last->setOperations(S);\n    else\n      Last->State =          │
│ TreeEntry::NeedToGather;\n    Last->ReorderIndices.append(...);\n\nThis       │
│ guarantees that any node lacking a valid InstructionsState is treated as a    │
│ gather and won't invoke E->getMainOp()/E->getOpcode() in cost                 │
│ computation.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe crash stems from creating a               │
│ Vectorize-state TreeEntry without a valid InstructionsState when reordering   │
│ scalars yields an invalid opcode analysis. By downgrading such entries to     │
│ NeedToGather during newTreeEntry construction, we prevent later accesses to S │
│ in getEntryCost, eliminating the assertion. This is consistent with the       │
│ vectorizer's fallback behavior and keeps scheduler/bundle logic intact        │
│ (non-gathers only)."})                                                        │
